Barack Obama is the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and $1.4 million check will be awarded, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have a lot to do.
First, visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with the five members of the committee that, in October, chose him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled for a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive him, but the third to receive him in office.
The White House has already announced that, when it receives the prize, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased even more with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the check of ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to donate charitable paraffins, but it has not yet decided which organization in particular.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which they will attend, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he did not deserve it entirely.
He also repeated several times that the award is not just for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents “a challenge to take action.”
