Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comic that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it proved to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "as in Iraq" used several times in the same text, but he also hesitated to use the title of the January 2007 Bush declaration for his own declaration: "A new way forward."
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, proved that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today there is no talk about Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, but it objectively left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially Afghan Operation Chief Commander General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the indecisive gunmen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He called for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but nothing better happened to him, so at least he deceived the general over 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of all Obama’s strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will yield the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is met.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces if they are accustomed to changing their boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action," a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy shocks by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war so that they "come home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, fixing the date for the withdrawal of the troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of the American defeat.
The recent NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, and do not want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
The answers will need to be sought precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of its troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic reversal for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years to the presidential election and therefore there is still a lot of time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
