The senior executives of Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
The entity announced it to react to the harsh criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 senior executives will receive, instead of money, shares that cannot be sold in a minimum period of five years.
In addition, the shares may be withdrawn in the event that they have assumed excessive risks.
According to Reuters, Goldman Sachs has thus become the leader in the effort to unite Wall Street bonuses with long-term power.
I suppose Wall Street is fully aware of the longest path it has to take, said former JPMorgan banking investor Douglas Elliott.
The problem is in the details, he added.
Goldman Sachs faced the criticism after removing $17 billion (nearly CZK 300 billion) for bonuses in the first three quarters of this year.
The total amount of bonuses in the entity for this year, according to Reuters, is likely to exceed, despite the measure announced today, $20 billion.
High bonuses in the banking sector became, with the arrival of the financial crisis, a delicate topic in politics.
Britain announced on Wednesday that it plans to levy a one-time tax of fifty percent on bank bonuses exceeding £25,000 (approximately CZK 712,000).
France is also preparing similar measures.
This year, women were awarded the Nobel Prize in all categories except physics.
Five women, which is a record number, received this year’s Nobel Prizes in specialized categories and literature in Stockholm from King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden.
In addition to the four scientists, among the award winners was also a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for their research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Israelis Ada Jonath and Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for their explanation of the structure and function of ribosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to American economist Elinor Ostrom and his fellow economist Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without a woman awarded, was Physics.
This award was awarded to scientists Charles Kao for their research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which constitutes the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each laureate received a diploma, a Nobel medal and a certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 25 million Czech crowns).
If there are several prize winners in each category, the prize is shared between them.
