The secret of the splendor over Norway solved: the Russians tested a missile
Over Norway a special light effect of unknown origin was observed.
Russia’s Defense Ministry has acknowledged that it has tested an intercontinental ballistic missile near its border with Norway.
The Bulava-type missile, previously intended to be the pride of the Russian army, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Even their repeated presence in missile tests has not had the desired effect on the success of the test flights.
Bulavá, in most cases, did not fly or a failure in the air occurred.
Russian newspapers write of Bulava as “a missile that does not fly.”
A missile that does not fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, no problems occurred at first.
At the end of the flight there were again technical problems in the aircraft.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulavá" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile makes it possible to launch from a ship that is moving and submerged at the same time.
That’s why it’s likely that the mysterious light on Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed “Bulavá.”
The Norwegians from the very beginning did not hesitate that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by saying that one cannot simply speak of a failure.
The first two stages of the missile ended and the crash occurred in the third.
In the previous cases, the engines were immediately damaged in the first stage.
Although none of the launches took place completely without errors, according to the Ministry of Defense management, only six of the thirteen were failed.
The success of almost fifty percent fills the generals with optimism and therefore they continue to say that "Bulavá" one day will fly without problems and that it will even manage to carry up to ten nuclear hypersonic blocks, whose maximum total weight is 1.15 tons.
