Hyundai Complies with Trade Union Requirements, Cancels All Supplementary Work
The management of the automobile factory in Nošovice agreed with the unions to cancel all additional work.
Due to the frequent additional work, the unions declared a strike emergency on Monday.
This was confirmed by Petr Vaněk, a spokesman for Hyundai Motor Company.
This year, however, the leadership wants to agree with the trade unions on another turn on Saturday.
We can’t give up on our manufacturing plan, as it’s essential.That’s why we’ve proposed voluntary additional work for Saturday, December 19, that is, it’s going to be worked in two turns, Vaněk said.
According to the server Sedmička.cz, the company offered a bonus of 400 CZK to employees who work on the Saturday shift.
The bonus will also be paid for last Saturday, November 28.
According to Vaňka, the company decided to change the way it motivates its employees with the additional work offered.
Employees can charge the bonus for overtime or they can take a day off on December 28, that is, extend Christmas holidays in one day, Vaněk mentioned.
In addition, all employees of the Saturday shifts will receive money for the trip and for food.
Because supplementary work was the most urgent and problematic point of comments and complaints from trade unionists and strikers, who stopped manufacturing last week, management yesterday afternoon decided to immediately cancel all supplementary work for December, Vaněk mentioned.
Employees at the car factory were forced to work two more hours in addition to eight-hour shifts and this situation lasted virtually every day until last week.
After the agreement is signed, the unions will cancel the strike.
Another negotiation between the factory management and the trade unions should take place on Monday morning.
Trade union leader Petr Kuchař said on Wednesday that if they commit to meeting the requirements and the document is signed, they are ready to cancel the emergency by strike.
The situation in the automobile factory worsened last week on Wednesday, when about 400 employees spontaneously went on strike for frequent additional jobs.
They also protested against poor payment conditions and alleged harassment.
The management thought that employees had to work overtime to meet the requirements and be able to supply the cars.
The unionists in their declaration of the strike emergency on Monday also demanded that none of the employees, who last Wednesday interrupted the manufacture, be penalized in any way.
As far as supplementary work is concerned, unions demand that the company reduce it to a minimum.
In addition, this year they require a salary of 5,000 crowns for this work.
Hyundai’s Nošovice automobile plant currently employs 2,000 people.
Serial production began last November.
Until last September, it produced approximately 80,000 cars; its current production potential is 200,000 cars a year.
A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even in ‘Called’ HIV Viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus as some affordable drugs already do.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the lives of patients can be significantly extended thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metal-carborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Carbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all medicines used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, the scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus’s albumin.
Carbon metals have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, HIV virus fractionation does not occur and matured and infectious corpuscles of the virus would not be created.
If we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a news release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective.
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was carried out on probeta, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metal-carbonates on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which drugs often do not work.
