Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have sought to ban the construction of minarets and where there is a widespread warning about the alleged Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, a U.S. academic, has written a detailed report and studied the possible integration of Muslims (who are actually being integrated) into one of the most openly secular societies on the continent.
Some readers will come to this new book as admirers of the author’s latest work “Why the French Don’t Like Headcarves” (2006), an elegant and detailed study of a problem that divided and concerned the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects are still perceived today.
Mr. Bowen’s latest book has a broader and more ambitious perspective.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now provide the 5-6 million Muslims of France with what Mr. Bowen calls “Islamic spaces.”
He is a good listener who reproduces debates between teachers and students on the questions that most interest them.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or in a town hall (or both)?
Should they teach young Muslims about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it legitimate for a Muslim to use a interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly worldly issues, he says, things of everyday life that concern the media more than political dramas.
The author identifies a new generation of imams, professors and intellectuals, none of them renowned, with the possible exception of Tariq Ramadan, an Arab Muslim academic and scholar born in Switzerland.
This new generation tries to open the debate on how to be both a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They cannot spread this argument fully.
Conservatives only doubt the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Mr. Bowen interviews tend to disagree with his Salafi counterparts, supporters of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia, who currently have a small but influential presence among Muslims in Europe.
Bowen thinks that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But adaptation requires mutual concessions.
It questions to what extent French political strategists (and the intellectual elite that so fiercely defends secularism) are really committed to pluralism.
It suggests that Muslims are probably treated more unfairly than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who have also had to make their historical commitments to secular republicanism.
More than a growing pragmatism, he perceives “a adjustment of values.”
After reading this book, one tends to say “Yes, but not yet.”
