A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, so far characterized by challenging positions and mutual reproaches, captured renewed attention on Friday with the disclosure of a document that predicts ambitious reductions in greenhouse gas emissions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying on their shoulders most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the path to follow.
But it was seen as a major step forward in a negotiation that is leaving out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Elaborated by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money rich countries would give to the poor to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal output, and what would be the limit of the global temperature rise that policy strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, a senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summed up a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as “the great panorama.”
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also boosted talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, on Friday, the same kind of verbal fireworks were presented that have dominated conversations last week.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change, Todd Stern, has rejected claims calling for mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from some of the major emerging economies, if they weren’t funded by the developed world.
The exercise indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, compared to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also lamented that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China economically cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world’s major powers at stake, the fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing over their respective obligations, while the poorer nations insist that the world’s twenty-four most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rica delegate, said it’s not surprising that major powers are discussing who should pay for the expenses to limit greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive trying to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, Ulate argued, who also works as regional adviser on climate change for Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the most vulnerable countries to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say the talks will ultimately produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push of small island nations has "set political pressure on the entire political process," in part because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
