Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than a decade ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to “values” determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, business intelligence “requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision”; it requires employee commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange’s survey of its employees, encourage managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I fear not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Lastly, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology mechanistically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behavioral theory that American “neurosciences” have recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media have widely spread behind them.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the “command” (sic) of executives’ commitment, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms executives in a mechanistic management posture, unadapted to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating in every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivation.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilizing factors, business executives can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “on the spot”.
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for "just war" Obama receives praise from the right
On Friday, the American right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States, hailed the Obama speech on Thursday.
Conservatives, who had discredited the award to Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice president candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, Ms. Palin, a leading figure of the Republican party’s right wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of war “sometimes necessary” in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing the Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
Terrorists must be stopped, he said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself, on Thursday in Oslo, to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, the former House president rejoiced, who appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
For moments, the speech seemed to me very historic, Gingrich said during an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, whom some consider a possible candidate for the Republican investidura for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free or could deliver a peace prize if the recourse to force did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush’s speeches and current chronicler for the Washington Post, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a “world citizen,” as “always does,” he “speaks like a U.S. president” by reminding Europeans “that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the few right-wing not very convinced, a Bush-era falcon, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as “monotonous, pretentious and lacking inspiration” on the Internet site National Review Online.
On the left of the president, Democratic representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
The Los Angeles Times, although still believing Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech "superproduction" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression," the newspaper commented enthusiastically.
Obama "pronounced the speech that was necessary," the New York Times estimated, judging it "at the same time shady and edifying."
Road transport: three marathon negotiations to ensure Christmas supply
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, road trade unions and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only patronal organization that remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday afternoon that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat that falls on the Christmas supply.
During the signing session on Friday night, state transport secretary Dominique Bussereau "rejoiced" over the deal, following several negotiations that began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators said goodbye at Friday’s dawn in the hope of quickly signing the agreed text at the end of the morning.
Three employers’ organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTHER) withdrew.
But a meeting of more than six hours that began at 11 o’clock was necessary for everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 18 o’clock.
The conflict “would have been very damaging to” and “it was feared to disrupt the end-of-year holidays,” Bussereau said.
The text foresees an increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest wages (international transport).
The hourly fee will rise from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros for low wages.
It’s not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
If so, we will order our militants that there are no more cuts or blockades in the supply centers.
But there can always be some disconforming rebel, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that it was "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases to high wages given international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros monthly for the low wages and from 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It’s a common sense agreement that respects the wages, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognized it as “an historic agreement.”
For Richard Jaubert (CGT) it is “an acceptable commitment.”
The agreement also envisages an increase in travel expenses of 3% and the holding of general assemblies of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will allow, above all, to address the issue of an extraordinary payment and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a 100 million euro reduction in employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the rectification funding bill for 2009, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "under the same terms".
The signature of TLF allows the agreement to be applied, first, to the companies joining this organization and, secondly, to the entire profession, in case the Minister of Labour makes an extension.
It will be done “as soon as possible,” Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced that it was a "naive business", as the 100 million euros "were already promised to the sector to compensate for part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transportation forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but not to frustrate those who want to eat turkey at the upcoming Christmas dinner, the Unostra lamented.
The agreement puts at risk “the stability of very small and medium-sized enterprises in the sector over the next 12 months.”
RER A: Conflicts during the weekend, unions disconform with the proposals of the RATP
Conflicts on RER A, France’s largest urban public transportation line, will continue during the weekend, because at Friday’s meeting, the second day of strike between unions and the RATP leadership, there was no agreement and unions were dissatisfied with their request for a premium.
