The RER crosses the city of Paris from west to east.
The RATP route runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, approximately one in two trains circulated in peak hours, and almost no train in valley hours, as planned.
On Thursday there was no disorder on the slopes thanks to the organization of the inhabitants of the Island of France.
In this way, at dawn, the station of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less crowded than usual, especially due to the absence of students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), Jack Nbakina, a 29-year-old engineer, explained that he had gotten up “an hour and a half earlier to get to schedule.”
The Saint-Lazare station was not saturated, the SNCF said, which had planned the surveillance of police and law enforcement.
The RER A operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from the Saint-Lazare station to join the meters.
New general assemblies of striking workers will take place on Saturday and Sunday, analyzing the results, "not satisfactory" according to the unions, of a meeting that was held with the management on Friday afternoon.
The director of the RER proposes to negotiate a specific protocol in all aspects for the RER A: working time, professional development, etc.
This is not what drivers want to claim a premium they owe, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even puts between parentheses its premium proposals, the CGT commented indignantly, noting that the management "was not able to solve a problem that the SNCF and the road sector had already solved".
A new meeting is planned on Monday to carry out “a more extensive analysis of the conditions for the exercise of the profession,” the RATP said.
What also led the unions to say that the company “did not care about weekend users.”
In the morning, about 150 drivers stormed a committee at the headquarters in Paris.
Then the leadership, which until then refused to dialogue during the strike, suggested the meeting “to calm the waters.”
The conflict could spread to RER B on Tuesday, after the Unsa and the Independents have submitted a preliminary notice.
The unions demand a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros, of which 30 euros are variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Indépendants) and complain of the degradation of working conditions on this line that has a million daily passengers.
RER drivers, all in the second degree of their professional career, charge from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross and from 600 to 650 euros of premiums, for hours with alternating turns, Sundays and holidays.
Turkish court dissolves prokurd party, decision with serious consequences
Turkey's Constitutional Court failed on Friday to dissolve the country's main prokurd party, a decision that immediately provoked rage demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just handed out a hand to the Kurdish community trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The party of the Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that damaged the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the court president Hasim Kiliç told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes was needed to obtain the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party’s leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and deputy Aysel Tugluk, are excluded from political life for five years.
Also, the judge announced the cessation of parliamentary immunity of which Turk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of party assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 banks in the Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that deputies would leave Parliament before being parliamentarians without a party label.
The decision comes following a procedure launched by the Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007 that accuses the DTP of obeying the “principles” of the Kurdish Workers’ Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Numerous observers believe that the DTP is the legal political escape of the PKK rebels.
However, the party says it has no "organic ties" with the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government gives a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus put an end to the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to a rise in tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where a large number of protests against the conditions of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan’s detention have degenerated into clashes with police over the past few weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP locations in Diyarbakir, the large county in the southeast mostly populated by Kurds.
The Order Forces threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov bombs or stones.
In Istanbul, about 100 people were also gathered.
Following the verdict, Türk said the court’s decision would “deep the discouragement.”
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdistan, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
We are opposed to the closure of parties.
This is not the case, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack in which seven soldiers were killed three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
