The Dinosaur's Cradle
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-foot-long and 1.50-foot-high animal running on the two strong rear legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with fox-shaped tails and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of millions of years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived around 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogy, spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began in 2006 an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is something unprecedented for Trias sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Natural History Museum.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected.
Discovery confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the Sauridae were divided into their three most important genealogy: the carnivorous teropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivorous (saurs with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt and colleagues' analysis, Tawa hallae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae researchers found clues to air bags, such as those also possessed by the descendants of the teropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, birds are more efficient in breathing than mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag teropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, the researchers deduce that the saurs originated there for the first time.
Consequently, the three genealogy lineages separated at the outset and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other not very intimately related teropods.
The three cannot descend from a single related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration toward North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents too.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted picture, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is barely anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare reptile collateral line to Mesozoic dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
In the Trias, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other sauri.
Towards the end of the Trias dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the parenthood extinguished at the limit of the Trias to the Jurassic.
Success stories are not eternal.
There are two possibilities to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to defeat the adversaries in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact stopped the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Trias and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
From Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
Professors from the University of Toronto, Cambridge, Vienna or Berkeley, California participate.
Teachers from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen participate.
The police evacuation of the occupied casino at the Goethe University in Frankfurt impacted the world.
278 professors and lecturers from Goethe University, although also from higher education centres across Germany, Europe and North and South America, show solidarity with students in protest at the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they “reject” the police displacement promoted by the board of directors.
