The Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten Moscow districts, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret weapons research.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Here are important research and production centers of micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted the Riedberg scientific headquarters in Frankfurt, with university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
Several mutual visits were made and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign in Frankfurt a "Protocol of close collaboration".
Moscow deputy mayor Juri Rosljak and mayor of Selengrad, Anatoly Smirnov, headed the Russian delegation; by Frankfurt signed chief of planning services Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises of the research center for natural sciences will travel to a seminar in Selenograd.
Scientific exchanges
This is a continuous scientific exchange.
But it also deals with commercial relations.
FIZ companies will have the opportunity to set foot in the growing Russian market.
In exchange, Russian research companies want access to contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is the seat of important Russian companies and research institutes.
Among them are, for example, the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large consortiums Sitronics and Rossijskaja Elektronika.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so-called "Socialist Planning City" for arms research.
Selenograd (literally translated as "Green City") received its name from the landscape of forested mountains, in which research facilities were established.
Brakes in Stuttgart
The Stuttgart Dimension 21 is not placed for anything high enough.
For the supporters of the project it is simply and smoothly “the new heart of Europe”.
S21 is much more than the reduction of a railway station, more than a monstrous construction project, which will precipitate to the capital of the Banden-Württemberg region a decade of chaos of irreparable construction sites.
Stuttgart 21 emerged from the spirit of the 1980s.
Railway terminals, which end in the middle of the city, were then considered to be 19th-century engineering fossils, which acted as brakes for modern railway traffic, since it used to take an enormous amount of time to plug the locomotives backwards.
Roll, stop in dry, continue the journey; but so it must be done.
And that’s why the terminals had to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a passing station, which is located approximately halfway from the route of the trans-European operating lines between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava; hence the slogan of "Heart of Europe".
The S21 will really be started, even though the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious designers have known that in the Hessian and Bavarian capitals it is almost impagable to implement the reduction.
Railway terminals, of course, do not have any more entrance and exit problems, since there are reversible locomotives with tractor unit and driver car at both ends.
However: Stuttgart 21 including the new ICE-built route to Ulm will already be started.
Federal and local governments have decided so.
The railway continues, also because the risks of the Republic’s large individual infrastructure projects are borne by the taxpayer and not the state.
From the urban point of view, the project is still justified to some extent.
A new urban space is created, provided with many green areas, probably from the computer-generated graphics of the designer.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The passing station and road support are intended for people transportation, which was attributed to the huge growth typical of the 1980s.
At that time, there was no competition for low-cost flights.
But modern transportation policy must first deal with strengthening freight transportation, as rail transportation is considerably more environmentally friendly than that carried out by trucks on the roads.
However, the new tracks under construction are good for cargo trains due to the intense gradients.
Even worse is that the S21 also indirectly affects many other railway projects.
More than 6 billion euros must be buried in the Zuavos.
That is the official figure.
Experts consider it more realistic between ten and fifteen billion.
It is certain that in the next decade money will be missing in other crossings and narrow passages in the network.
A total of 60 major projects are on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the expansion of more than 180 kilometers of long rails through the Rhin valley.
Since 1987 the trail has been built slowly.
It would be urgent here to step the accelerator properly.
However, the S21 acts as a brake.
The Rhine Valley section will be the bottleneck for international freight transportation: through the heart of Europe.
