In a state of alertness, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of mentally ill people and drug addicts the boundaries between imagination and reality fade away.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we lie down in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can surrender unhinderedly to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is considered most of the time in the modern Western world as a madman or drug addict, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drugged.
The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between dream, madness and reality fade.
Alert states modified onirically can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to by the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, shamanic possession states, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communicating substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – is disrupted and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During a schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and mad thoughts often appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a state of vigilance, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with the onyrical states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the dishonesty, allocated formations, and mirrors of this."
