The cause of this was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, in addition he is manic-depressive, takes medication, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, and has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of over-excitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, relationship disorders, or persecutory mania.
Specifically spread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis opens the doors to a stream of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says professor Thomas Fuchs, chief medical officer at the general psychiatric clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations rely on reality, distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, it is still unclear why our brains make crabs.
According to Fuchs, exceptional states can cause anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
Apparently there is a genetic predisposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
The researchers assume that the affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which is not manifested at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a pre-disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmission system.
When the brain gets hot
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten, of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as boundary personality disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and cranioencephal trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally found to be suppressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or are poorly curbed; when our brain warms up, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or a psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, love illness or other exceptional brain states.
