Difference between sleep and hallucination
In this world too centered on the conscious, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and head of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a tough and painful illness but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
Conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or illness, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of his own and imaginary that is disconnected from reality.
This is the boundary between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own ability to create allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory.
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, from Zurich, also describes his onyrical experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a salvation action of the soul.
He was 49 when his consciousness embarked on several-day trips after a heart valve operation with heart transplant included, while his body was condemned to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was laid down in bed, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium in a train, a robot watched for his health.
He was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
