75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study ‘Fecundity and labor trajectory of women in Spain’, prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 left no doubt: 75% of working mothers saw limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation in a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, initiate prior cohabitation in a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged between 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time of their life trajectory to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exercises a lot of influence on maternity even less on the calendar of mating,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another of the factors that differentiate the age of women when they get married and when they have the first rapture.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the greater the age at which they marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years old, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average, respectively.
"There is also another division among women according to their level of education.
While those who have elementary studies marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and prioritize obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child,” Delgado says.
