Emergency Braking Assistance is Now Mandatory
As with ABS brake anti-locking and ESP stability control, emergency brake assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new-matriculated passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest there is a period of shortage until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency braking assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s pitch.
But he doesn’t always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision, and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four crashes with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called smart emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exercises maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
